{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533199"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:34:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:34:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14764"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14764"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.1,0.61,0.11,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74798"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7455"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60284"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3643"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18247"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74798"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERabies is a viral infection that causes progressive neurological dysfunction. The virus enters the body through broken skin, typically from an animal bite.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism by which rabies virus causes neurological damage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct neurotoxin production","Destruction of anterior horn cells","Retrograde axonal transport with direct viral damage","Neuromuscular junction blockade","Spinal cord inflammation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERabies virus causes neurological symptoms through a distinct pathophysiological process. The virus initially binds to nicotinic acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction to gain entry into neurons. It then travels to the central nervous system via \u003Cstrong\u003Eretrograde axonal transport with direct viral damage\u003C/strong\u003E. This process, combined with the inflammatory response, leads to neuronal dysfunction and death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect neurotoxin production\u003C/strong\u003E is not the mechanism by which rabies virus causes paralysis. Unlike bacteria such as \u003Cem\u003EClostridium tetani\u003C/em\u003E, rabies virus does not produce a specific neurotoxin. Instead, the virus directly infects and damages neurons.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDestruction of anterior horn cells\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of poliovirus infection, not rabies. Poliovirus specifically targets motor neurons in the anterior horn of the spinal cord, leading to asymmetric flaccid paralysis. In contrast, rabies virus affects neurons throughout the nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuromuscular junction blockade\u003C/strong\u003E is not how rabies virus causes paralysis. While the virus uses nicotinic acetylcholine receptors for initial entry, it does not block neuromuscular transmission like botulinum toxin or certain snake venoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpinal cord inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E, while present, is not the primary mechanism of paralysis. The virus causes damage through direct neuronal infection after travelling up peripheral nerves, rather than primarily through inflammatory processes in the spinal cord.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe progression of neurological symptoms typically follows the pattern of viral spread, starting at the site of infection and moving centrally as the virus travels through the nervous system to reach the brainstem and cerebral cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rabies virus causes paralysis through retrograde axonal transport to the central nervous system.","Direct viral damage and inflammatory responses in the brain lead to neuronal dysfunction.","Rabies virus glycoprotein binds to nicotinic acetylcholine receptors to enter neurons.","The virus spreads from peripheral nerves to the central nervous system causing progressive neurological dysfunction."],"references":["Fooks AR, Cliquet F, Finke S, et al. Rabies. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017;3:17091. Published 2017 Nov 30. doi:10.1038/nrdp.2017.91","Davis BM, Rall GF, Schnell MJ. Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Rabies Virus (But Were Afraid to Ask). Annu Rev Virol. 2015;2(1):451-471. doi:10.1146/annurev-virology-100114-055157"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60284"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14764"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60284"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T07:04:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T07:05:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7455"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74798"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{